  "nursesNote": "In somatic symptom disorder the patient has real, distressing physical symptoms along with excessive thoughts and anxiety about them; in conversion disorder there is a loss of function (such as paralysis, blindness, or pseudo-seizures) with no medical explanation, sometimes with surprising calm about the deficit (la belle indifference). These symptoms are not intentionally produced, unlike malingering (faking for external gain) or factitious disorder (faking for the sick role). The nurse first ensures a medical cause has been ruled out, then acknowledges that the symptoms feel real and never confronts the patient or says it is 'all in your head.' The nurse avoids reinforcing the symptoms with excessive attention or secondary gain, stays matter-of-fact, and gently redirects to feelings, stress, and coping skills.",
  "providerOrders": [
    "Ensure a medical cause has been ruled out",
    "Acknowledge the symptoms are real to the patient",
    "Do not confront or say the symptoms are imagined",
    "Avoid reinforcing symptoms or secondary gain",
    "Redirect to feelings, stress, and coping skills"
  ],
